dismissalText.commentary: Kyle Coetzer c Mire b Williams 109 (101b 13x4 2x6) SR: 107.92

dismissalComment.html: If Scotland were in a worse situation, a headline would be writing itself. Coetzer is out after sweeping to deep midwicket where Solomon Mire takes the simple catch. What a knock from the captain, second century this week.

dismissalComment.html: Third wicket down. Berrington drives to midwicket where the captain Cremer takes a lovely diving catch low down. Great catch.

dismissalComment.html: The danger man is gone. Williams looked like he could bat Zimbabwe to victory, but he goes to cut a slower ball and edges behind to Cross.

commentTextItems.html: smashed high in the air to mid on where Sole takes the catch.

commentPostTextItems.html: So Scotland win their first ever ODI against a test nation. A historic win, and an entertaining game. Waller and Williams could have won the game for Zimbabwe with superb hitting, but Scotland's batting performance gave them a platform that gave
The second ODI will be played on Saturday. See you there to see if Zimbabwe can level the series, or will Scotland win a series against a test team? See you then!

commentTextItems.html: cut down to third man for a single
yorker, tapped into the leg side for a single
single to Ngarava
defended

commentPostTextItems.html: That was a superb knock from Waller. Nearly took Zimbabwe from a huge loss, to an extraordinary win.
Sharif to bowl the final over from the Pavillion End.

swept in the air, but lands just inside the rope and fielded
Waller sweeps, but top edges it to mid on. No run
And this is why. Smashed way over the mid on boundary for six. Lost the ball again.
flicked down to fine leg. Chatara wants a run, Waller stays.
yorker, defended to midwicket for a single.

commentPostTextItems.html: De Lange replaces Berrington from the Nursery End. Can he get his fifth wicket?

commentTextItems.html: tapped into the leg side for  a single. Waller back on strike
hit back up to long on for a single
swing and a miss. Better ball from Sharif
yorker, and cut away for four runs

commentPostTextItems.html: Waller's strike-rate is 151.85. Says it all.

commentTextItems.html: big swing, edged behind for four runs. This is getting very tense
swept down to fine leg for a single, the boundary is stopped by Wallace. 250 up for Zimbabwe

commentPostTextItems.html: Sharif replaces Sole from the Pavillion End

dismissalComment.html: Williams cuts to point, and they go for a dodgy run. Berrington fields and the thrown goes to the striker's End and the stumps are taken out. Brilliant fielding!

dismissalText.commentary: Ryan Burl b de Lange 8 (9b 1x4 0x6) SR: 88.88

dismissalComment.html: And that's the fifth wicket down, de Lange beating Burl to bowl him. Scorecard pressure?

dismissalText.commentary: Sean Williams c Cross b Berrington 70 (59b 9x4 1x6) SR: 118.64

dismissalComment.html: The danger man is gone. Williams looked like he could bat Zimbabwe to victory, but he goes to cut a slower ball and edges behind to Cross.

dismissalText.commentary: Malcolm Waller c Sole b de Lange 92 (62b 10x4 5x6) SR: 148.38

dismissalComment.html: This has to be the game for Scotland. Waller sweeps to deep square leg where Sole takes the catch on the boundary rope. Waller doesn't want to go, saying Sole has overstepped the rope, but the umpire tells him to go. Seven behind his top score.
